C¶

All comments in this part assumes a visual classification after the dimension reductions. For example, it is pretty obvious that MDS with L1 Norm results in a classification as x<-1.5 || x > 1.5 => class a else class b.

1- PCA results in a fair discrimination in terms of classes of the data. However some of the points around 125-150 are coincide with the other class points in 1-D. Therefore, it seems mostly successfull despite those misclassified points. 2- MDS with L1 Norm seems even better than L2 Norm as there seems only 1 data point which is misclassified visually. 3- MDS with L2 Norm seems performing better than PCA as there is almost no points with wrong classification. As a result, MDS is more successfull than PCA in this particular problem.

In [82]:

Out[83]:
array([0.71943753, 0.28056247])

While in the first part, we could explain 72% variation with one component, now, with the addition of nonlinear terms, it reduced to 41%. Therefore, we could claim that the addition of interaction or nonlinear terms would not be beneficial in PCA.

In [266]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_figwidth(30)
fig.set_figheight(30)
ax.scatter(dd[0], dd[1])

for i, city in enumerate(distmat.columns):
    ax.annotate(city, (dd[0][i], dd[1][i]), size  = 20)

As seen, it seems pretty close to the actual Turkey map. However, there seems to be some distance Samsun-Ordu, Tokat-Erzincan, Sivas-Elaz, Kayseri-Malatya region. This may be an indicator of the mountainous terrain over that part of Turkey. Since MDS looks at the dissimilarity (road distance in our case), not the actual locations of the data points, it takes into account the geographical factors such as height and other physical existings on the roads (rivers, mountains, etc.). Therefore, it is expected that even if the distance between two cities by birds eye is small but the road is passing through mountainous terrain, then in this scatter plot the distance would seem longer.

To get the velocity vectors:

In [315]:

ztrain_v = ztrain.loc[:, ztrain.columns!=0].cumsum(axis = 1)

To get the position vectors:

In [316]:

ztrain_p = ztrain_v.cumsum(axis = 1)

The patterns in the plots shows clearly that each dimension has its own eigenvector pattern independent of each other, that is, the time series is not smooth as the transition from one dimension to another is clearly seen.In all 8 classes different dimension variations are attributed to different vectors. That is, the variation explained by the first eigenvector corresponds mostly to variation in the first dimension in class 5, e.g.
